adbach death drama about graffiti sprayer (29): captured by train - dead|date=20 May 2016|work=express.de|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bahnblogstelle.net/2016/05/20/vom-zug-erfasst-graffiti-sprayer-verunglueckt-auf-bahnanlage-in-moenchengladbach/|title=Vom Zug erfasst \u2013 Graffiti-Sprayer verungl\u00fcckt auf Bahnanlage in M\u00f6nchengladbach|date=20 May 2016|work=bahnblogstelle|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|03 October 2016}}\n|Germany - Berlin\n|Hit by Train\n|18,19\n|Two people, aged 18 and 19, were hit by a train; a bag with spray utensils and spray paint cans were found nearby.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/polizei-justiz/berlin-wilhelmsruh-zwei-graffiti-sprayer-von-s-bahn-ueberrollt-und-getoetet/14634642.html|title=Two graffiti sprayers run over by S-Bahn and killed|last=Hasselmann|first=Jorn|date=10 May 2016||work=Der Tagesspiegel|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bz-berlin.de/berlin/pankow/zwei-jugendliche-anscheinend-beim-sprayen-von-s-bahn-ueberfahren|title=Zwei Jugendliche beim Sprayen von S-Bahn \u00fcberfahren|date=3 October 2016||work=BZ|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bild.de/regional/berlin/zugunglueck/jugendliche-sprayer-von-s-bahn-ueberrollt-48115544.bild.html|title=2 SPRAYERS CAUGHT BY TRAIN - DEAD!Did the youngsters just want to cross the tracks?|last=Kroning|first=Ole||last2=Lier|first2=Axel|date=10 May 2016||work=Der Tagesspiegel|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|29 May 2017}}\n|Australia - Sydney\n|Hit by train\n|25\n|A 25-year-old person was allegedly spraying graffiti on a stationary train, but ran across the tracks and were hit by a train. Items such as graffiti spray cans and coverings for the face were found nearby.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-29/suspected-graffiti-vandal-killed-after-hit-by-sydney-train/8567718/|title=Suspected graffiti vandal dies after being hit by train at Kingsgrove in Sydney's south|date=29 May 2017|work=ABC News(Australia)|access-date=29 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theleader.com.au/story/4691833/kingsgrove-train-death-linked-to-graffiti/|title=Man found dead on train tracks at Kingsgrove suspected of graffiti vandalism|date=29 May 2017|work=The Leader|access-date=29 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/kingsgrove-train-death-graffiti-vandal-struck-and-killed-on-tracks/news-story/dc5c183761e80441c26267338b70d227|title=Kingsgrove train death: Graffiti vandal struck and killed on tracks|date=29 May 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|30 August 2017}}\n|Greece - Athens\n|Electrocution\n|?\n|A person died at Thiseo station in Athens Greece. It is thought they had been attempting to paint graffiti between two train carriages and were electrocuted.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://int.ert.gr/young-frenchman-dies-while-spraying-graffiti-on-train-carriages-in-athens/|title=Young Frenchman dies while spraying graffiti on train carriages in Athens|work=ERT International|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.keeptalkinggreece.com/2017/08/31/french-dead-graffiti-athens/|title=Young Frenchman dies as he attempts graffiti on train wagons in Thiseio|date=31 August 2017|work=Keep Talking Greece|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|2018}}\n|Spain - Barcelona\n|Fall\n|?\n|A person fell 6 metres down a vent hole resulting in them going into a coma. By going down the vent hole the person would have been able to access railway property. The person continued to suffer from the injuries they received a year following the fall.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/02/20/inenglish/1550651731_094226.html|title=Marketer by day, warrior by night: Meet the graffiti artists risking their lives to paint Spain\u2019s trains|last=Pareja|first=Pol|date=22 February 2019|work=El Pais|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n|- \n|{{dts|18 June 2018}}\n|United Kingdom - London\n|Hit by train\n|19, 23, 23\n|Three people were killed when they were hit by a train between Brixton and Denmark Hill train stations. It is thought they saw an oncoming train and then hid behind a wall so that they would be hidden from sight.  In doing this they put themselves in the path of the train. Spray paint cans were in close proximity to where their bodies were found. Two were aged 23 and the third was 19.  They went by the tags \"Trip\", \"Kbag\" and \"Lover\".\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jun/19/tributes-graffiti-artists-killed-loughborough-junction-train-london|title=Tributes paid to three graffiti artists killed by train in south London|last=Weaver|first=Matthew|date=19 June 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=25 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Anny Shaw Art Newspaper\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/street-art-community-pays-tribute-to-three-graffiti-artists-killed-by-a-train-in-london|title=Street art community pays tribute to three graffiti artists killed by a train in London|last=Shaw|first=Anny|date=19 June 2018|work=The Art Newspaper|access-date=25 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-47404529|title=Loughborough Junction graffiti artists died hiding from train|last=Weaver|first=Matthew|date=28 February 2019|work=BBC|access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n|- \n|{{dts|04 December 2018}}\n|United Kingdom - Glasgow\n|Electrocution\n|29\n|A 29-year-old person, who went by the tag \"Mode\", was killed by what was thought to be electrocution. Police and ambulance services were called to the location where they was lying on the tracks near Dumbreck station in Glasgow at around 1am and they was pronounced dead at the scene.  A 29-year-old person who was with him at the time was initially arrested for trespass and vandalism and then later released without any charges against them being pursued.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/news/17280345.grant-hamilton-heartfelt-tributes-to-mode-electrocuted-to-death-on-tracks-near-dumbreck/|title=Arrest made as person \u2018electrocuted to death\u2019 on train tracks near Dumbreck|last=Ali|first=Aftab|date=4 December 2018|work=Glasgow Times|access-date=29 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/tragic-graffiti-artist-dies-after-13693481/|title=Tragic graffiti artist dies after being electrocuted on railway line in Glasgow|last=Pringle|first=Michael|date=6 December 2018|work=Daily Record|access-date=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|11 May 2019}}\n|Spain - Valencia\n|Hit by Car\n|14\n|A 14-year-old person, who went by the tag \"Koner\", was with a group of people on the side of a highway in Valencia. They had just painted ACM the name of their crew, on the side of the highway. The people with the 14 year-old traveled across the highway. The 14 year-old, holding a roller brush and paint can, then traveled across two lanes of the highway and was hit by an oncoming car. The 14 year-old had appeared on the highway unexpectedly in front of the travelling car. \n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lasprovincias.es/sucesos/menor-muere-atropellado-20190513003543-ntvo.html|title=A 14-year-old graffiti artist dies hit on the V-30 after making a graffiti on the new channel|last=Martinez|first=Javier|date=13 May 2019||work=Las Provincias|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lasprovincias.es/sucesos/sueno-roto-pintada-20190514002738-ntvo.html|title=A dream broken by a graffiti|last=Marrahi|first=Ja|date=15 May 2019||work=Las Provincias|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cadenaser.com/emisora/2019/05/12/radio_valencia/1557645947_726156.html|title=A young graffiti artist killed on the V-30 road dies|date=13 May 2019||work=Cadena SER|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|15 November 2019}}\n|United States - San Diego\n|Fall\n|28\n|A 28-year-old person, had been attempting to spray paint graffiti on a building when they fell through a metal awning and were subsequently killed.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.10news.com/news/local-news/san-diego-news/tagger-falls-to-his-death-in-san-diegos-east-village/|title=Tagger falls to his death in San Diego's East Village|last=Horn|first=Allison|date=15 November 2019||work=abc 10news|access-date=28 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.10news.com/news/local-news/tagger-identified-after-deadly-fall-from-east-village-building|title=Tagger identified after deadly fall from East Village building|work=abc 10news|last=Horn|first=Allison|date=15 November 2019||access-date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" class=\"center\">\nNeasden Depot Geograph 725783.jpg|[[Neasden Depot]] A graffiti writer who went by the tag \"Rase\", was electrocuted on a live rail at Neasden Depot in 1988.\nPeiraias metro.jpg|[[Piraeus station]] - Greece \nGraffiti_am_U-Bahnhof_Yorckstra\u00dfe_20150105_1.jpg|[[Berlin Yorckstra\u00dfe station]] \n1UP trainwriting in Berlin.jpg|Trainwriting 1UP Berliner S-Bahn \nGraffiti Railway Bridge Footscray, Melbourne Australia - Yr 2020.jpg|thumb|Railway bridge [[Footscray]] Melbourne Australia \nRailway bridge - West Melbourne, Melbourne Australia - Yr 2020.jpg|thumb|Railway bridge - [[West Melbourne, Victoria]] Australia \nTaken near Richmond train station - Melbourne Australia yr2020.jpg|Railway bridge - [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne]] Australia\nRENKS and ICE Graffiti tags on Industrial building near South Kensington Station - West Melbourne, Melbourne Australia - 2020.jpg|thumb|Graffiti near [[South Kensington railway station]] - West Melbourne, Australia\n\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Graffiti]]\n* [[Street art]]\n* [[List of selfie-related injuries and deaths]]\n* [[Rooftopping]]\n* [[List of train surfing injuries and deaths]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Accidents]]\n[[Category:Death-related lists]]\n[[Category:Health-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by cause of death]]\n[[Category:Graffiti and unauthorised signage]]\n", "name_user": "Xyxyzyz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGraffiti and street art injuries and deaths", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_graffiti_and_street_art_injuries_and_deaths"}
{"title_page": "Sign of the Pagan", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sign of the Pagan\n| image\t         =Sign_of_the_Pagan.jpg\n| caption        = [[Film poster]] by [[Reynold Brown]]\n| director       = [[Douglas Sirk]]\n| producer       = Albert J Cohen\n| writer         = [[Oscar Brodney]]<br>[[Barre Lyndon]]\n| based on       = story by [[Oscar Brodney]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]]<br>[[Jack Palance]]<br>[[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]]<br>[[Rita Gam]]\n| music          = [[Frank Skinner (composer)|Frank Skinner]]<br>[[Hans J. Salter]]\n| cinematography = [[Russell Metty]]\n| editing        = [[Al Clark (film editor)|Al Clark]]\n| studio         = Universal Pictures \n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1954|12|18|United States|1954|12|23|Los Angeles}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = $2.5 million (US rentals)<ref>'The Top Box-Office Hits of 1955', ''Variety Weekly'', January 25, 1956</ref>\n}}\n'''''Sign of the Pagan''''' is a 1954 American [[historical drama|historical drama film]] directed by [[Douglas Sirk]], shot in [[CinemaScope]] (color by [[Technicolor]]), and released by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film stars [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]], [[Jack Palance]], [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]], and [[Rita Gam]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/90104/Sign-of-the-Pagan/ ''Sign of the Pagan''] at [[TCMDB]]</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nDuring the fifth century, the [[Roman Empire]] is divided into two parts: the West, with its capital in Rome, run by Emperor [[Valentinian III]], and the East, with its capital in [[Constantinople]], run by Emperor [[Theodosius II|Theodosius]]. The Empire is under attack by the Huns under [[Attila]]. Roman soldier [[Marcian]] is carrying a message from Valentinian warning Theodosius against the Huns, when he is captured by Attila. Attila is impressed by Marcian's honesty and courage. He carves out the arrow that has been shot into his leg, causing Marcian to pass out. Over the next few days, Attila keeps Marcian hostage in the hopes of learning more about the Romans' plans. The Huns capture a local king's family and Attila orders them killed, except for the daughter, Ilduco, whom he takes as his wife. Later, when Attila's daughter, Kubra, shows off her father's prize stallion, Marcian steals it and flees to Constantinople.\n\nIn Constantinople, Marcian is befriended by General Paulinus, who confides that Theodosius is planning to join forces with the Huns against Valentinian. This is confirmed when Marcian brings his emperor's message to Theodosius, who throws him out. Theodosius' sister, Princess [[Pulcheria]], calls Marcian to her chambers. She admits that she loves Rome, but is kept prisoner within the palace walls. She names Marcian the captain of her guard, asking him to protect her from Theodosius' mutiny. That night, Theodosius holds a feast to welcome the Hun leaders. Although Attila has not been invited, he arrives to command the allegiance of all other Barbarians, and easily defeats the strongest man in Constantinople. Frightened, Theodosius offers him furs and jewels, but Attila demands only that Marcian teach the Huns how to use Roman weapons. Although Kubra is the first to practice with the weapons, Marcian deposits her in the harem bathing pool.\n\nLater, Pulcheria sends for Attila. She asks him to release Marcian from his duties, but Attila kisses her roughly and then leaves to meet Theodosius, who agrees to pay each month in return for Attila's promise not to attack. Later, Marcian also approaches the Hun, warning him that because Rome is Christian, it will never fall. Attila merely laughs at him, but when Kubra visits the church the next day, she is awed by the portrait of Mary and longs for the peace she feels there. She tries to refuse to leave, but Attila forces her to accompany the Huns out of the city. The next night, Attila gathers the Barbarian leaders and announces that they will attack Rome immediately. As soon as his soothsayer announces that the signs are positive, a bolt of lightning strikes a tree that falls on him. Although this concerns the Huns, Attila names it a good omen. Soon after, his men bring two captured monks to him, and Attila, who does not dare anger the Christian God, orders the soldiers killed. The monks then beg him not to kill the soldiers, baffling Attila.\n\nAs the Huns gather outside Rome, Marcian, finding no help for Valentinian with Theodosius, prepares to flee the palace, but is captured upon stopping to bid Pulcheria goodbye. While Attila's new seer, whom he calls Persian, relates a vision of Marcian as emperor, Paulinus releases Marcian from the dungeon and the two sneak into Pulcheria's. Together, they decide to gather the army against Theodosius and install Pulcheria to the throne. After Theodosius is forced to abdicate, Pulcheria names Marcian her top general and announces her plans to travel to Rome with him and their army to help guard its walls. Meanwhile, Persian is plagued by visions of God and martyrs in the clouds calling for Attila's death, and Attila remembers an image his childhood nurse saw in which he died under the shadow of a cross. Though fearful, he continues to disregard the signs. When Marcian reaches Rome, he finds Valentinian leaving, but retains two battalions to add to his own to protect the city.\n\nThat night, Attila orders the attack, but stops when [[Pope Leo I]] arrives to name Rome the temple of God and foresee Attila's downfall, as portended by the lightning strike. Afterward, Attila realizes that Kubra must have told the Pope about the lightning, and, though he is heartbroken, kills her for betraying him. In his sleep that night, he sees a vision of the martyrs marching against him and, crazed, orders the Huns to retreat. Marcian hears and immediately plans to ambush Attila when he reaches the nearest city. The surprise attack demolishes the Huns, who soon fall. Marcian finds Attila and duels with him, but it is Ildico, who has spent the last months overflowing with rage, who drives the fatal dagger into his chest. As prophesied, Attila dies with the sword's handle forming the shadow of a cross on the ground. Days later, Pulcheria reunites the halves of the empire and names Marcian emperor, to the delight of the Roman people.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]] as [[Marcian]]\n* [[Jack Palance]] as [[Attila]]\n* [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] as Princess [[Pulcheria]]\n* [[Rita Gam]] as Kubra\n* [[Jeff Morrow]] as General Paulinus\n* [[George Dolenz]] as Emperor [[Theodosius II]]\n* [[Eduard Franz]] as Astrologer\n* [[Allison Hayes]] as [[Ildico]]\n* [[Alexander Scourby]] as [[Chrysaphius]]\n* [[Howard Petrie]] as [[Gundahar]]\n* [[Michael Ansara]] as Edecon\n* [[Leo Gordon]] as [[Bleda]]\n* [[Moroni Olsen]] as [[Pope Leo I]]\n* Fred Nurney as Chamberlain\n* [[Sara Shane]] as Myra\n* [[Pat Hogan]] as [[Sangiban]]\n* Robo Bechi as Chilothe \n* Charles Horvath as Olt\n* Glenn Thompson as Seyte\n* Chuck Robertson as Mirrai\n* [[Walter Coy]] as Emperor [[Valentinian III]]\n* [[Rusty Westcoatt]] as Tula \n* Norbert Schiller as Seer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was announced by Universal in October 1953.<ref>{{cite news|title=U-I Will Continue Heavy Film Output: Studio Plan 34 Features for New Year in Contrast With Rivals' Cutback Program|first=Thomas M.|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times |date=27 October 1953|page= 32}}</ref> [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] was to make her dramatic debut in the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ballerina Doffs Shoes for Movie: Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina Will Make U. S. Film Debut in Dramatic Role in 'Sign of the Pagan'|author=Thomas M. Pryor|work=New York Times|date=26 November 1953|page=51}}</ref> She was a ballerina who had been signed to a long-term contract to Universal after a series of screen tests, including some with Jeff Chandler. Chandler was assigned the male lead and Douglas Sirk given the job of directing. The movie was going to be Universal's first using Cinemascope.<ref>{{cite news|title=Looking at Hollywood: 'Conquest of Space' to Be Film Without a Star|last=Hopper|first=Hedda|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=28 November 1953|page=15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dowling to Make Film of Hurricane: Tropic Storm to Be Protagonist of Movie Seen Through Eyes of Air Force Weather Men|last=Pryor|first=Thomas M.|work=New York Times|date=28 November 1953|page=11}}</ref> Jack Palance, then coming off a second Oscar nomination, soon signed to play Attila the Hun. Chandler told [[Hedda Hopper]] that the role was the best he had ever had and that the movie would be Universal's most expensive of that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: CinemaScope to Be Used for 'Venetian'|work=Los Angeles Times|date=7 December 1953|page=A14}}</ref>\n\nJeff Morrow had a two-film-a-year deal with Universal and appeared in ''Sign of the Pagan'' as the second film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Studios Explain Filming Abroad: Council Lists 5 Reasons for Rise -- Cites Backgrounds, Better Financing Deals|author=Thomas M. Pryor|work=New York Times|date=11 December 1953|page=42}}</ref> Allison Hayes was a model who was spotted by the wife of [[Earl Warren]] at a party in Washington. Mrs Warren suggested she try her luck in Hollywood and she succeeded in getting a contract with Universal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: 'Track of the Cat' Wellman's Next Film|work=Los Angeles Times|date=12 May 1954|page=B8}}</ref> She played Attila's young wife; Jack Palance injured her during their love scenes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: Fuller Will Direct Next Film in Britain|work=Los Angeles Times|date=29 January 1954|page=A6}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAnother film about Attila the Hun came out around the same time, ''Attila'', starring [[Anthony Quinn]] in the title role.<ref>{{cite news|title=Attila Strikes Twice|author=|work=New York Times|date=7 November 1954|page=SM78}}</ref>\n\nA novelisation of the script by Roger Fuller was published in 1955 in time for the film's release.<ref>{{cite news|title=With Toga and Gladius: Sign of the Pagan. By Roger Fuller. 373 pp. New York. Dial Press|last=Chubb|first=Thomas Caldecot|work=New York Times|date=9 January 1955|page=BR23}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed sequel==\nUniversal bought a script by Harold Lamb, ''Hannibal of Cathage'' as a possible sequel, to also star Jack Palance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: 'Hannibal of Carthage' Epical Project; Diana Lynn, Corey Stage Team|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=17 March 1954|page=19}}</ref> However, it was never made.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0047490}}\n*[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/90104/Sign-of-the-Pagan/ ''Sign of the Pagan''] at [[TCMDB]]\n*[https://archive.org/details/variety196-1954-11/page/n68/mode/1up/search/%22jeff+chandler%22?q=%22jeff+chandler%22 Review of film] at ''Variety'\n* {{YouTube|7Sfls2IjqzI|''Sign of the Pagan'' film clip}}\n\n{{Douglas Sirk |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sign Of The Pagan}}\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Douglas Sirk]]\n[[Category:1954 films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 5th century]]\n[[Category:1950s historical films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Attila the Hun]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Hans J. Salter]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sign of the Pagan\n| image\t         =Sign_of_the_Pagan.jpg\n| caption        = [[Film poster]] by [[Reynold Brown]]\n| director       = [[Douglas Sirk]]\n| producer       = Albert J Cohen\n| writer         = [[Oscar Brodney]]<br>[[Barre Lyndon]]\n| based on       = story by [[Oscar Brodney]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]]<br>[[Jack Palance]]<br>[[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]]<br>[[Rita Gam]]\n| music          = [[Frank Skinner (composer)|Frank Skinner]]<br>[[Hans J. Salter]]\n| cinematography = [[Russell Metty]]\n| editing        = [[Al Clark (film editor)|Al Clark]]\n| studio         = Universal Pictures \n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1954|12|18|United States|1954|12|23|Los Angeles}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = $2.5 million (US rentals)<ref>'The Top Box-Office Hits of 1955', ''Variety Weekly'', January 25, 1956</ref>\n}}\n'''''Sign of the Pagan''''' is a 1954 American [[historical drama|historical drama film]] directed by [[Douglas Sirk]], shot in [[CinemaScope]] (color by [[Technicolor]]), and released by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film stars [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]], [[Jack Palance]], [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]], and [[Rita Gam]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/90104/Sign-of-the-Pagan/ ''Sign of the Pagan''] at [[TCMDB]]</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nDuring the fifth century, the [[Roman Empire]] is divided into two parts: the West, with its capital in Rome, run by Emperor [[Valentinian III]], and the East, with its capital in [[Constantinople]], run by Emperor [[Theodosius II|Theodosius]]. The Empire is under attack by the Huns under [[Attila]]. Roman soldier [[Marcian]] is carrying a message from Valentinian warning Theodosius against the Huns, when he is captured by Attila. Attila is impressed by Marcian's honesty and courage. He carves out the arrow that has been shot into his leg, causing Marcian to pass out. Over the next few days, Attila keeps Marcian hostage in the hopes of learning more about the Romans' plans. The Huns capture a local king's family and Attila orders them killed, except for the daughter, Ilduco, whom he takes as his wife. Later, when Attila's daughter, Kubra, shows off her father's prize stallion, Marcian steals it and flees to Constantinople.\n\nIn Constantinople, Marcian is befriended by General Paulinus, who confides that Theodosius is planning to join forces with the Huns against Valentinian. This is confirmed when Marcian brings his emperor's message to Theodosius, who throws him out. Theodosius' sister, Princess [[Pulcheria]], calls Marcian to her chambers. She admits that she loves Rome, but is kept prisoner within the palace walls. She names Marcian the captain of her guard, asking him to protect her from Theodosius' mutiny. That night, Theodosius holds a feast to welcome the Hun leaders. Although Attila has not been invited, he arrives to command the allegiance of all other Barbarians, and easily defeats the strongest man in Constantinople. Frightened, Theodosius offers him furs and jewels, but Attila demands only that Marcian teach the Huns how to use Roman weapons. Although Kubra is the first to practice with the weapons, Marcian deposits her in the harem bathing pool.\n\nLater, Pulcheria sends for Attila. She asks him to release Marcian from his duties, but Attila kisses her roughly and then leaves to meet Theodosius, who agrees to pay each month in return for Attila's promise not to attack. Later, Marcian also approaches the Hun, warning him that because Rome is Christian, it will never fall. Attila merely laughs at him, but when Kubra visits the church the next day, she is awed by the portrait of Mary and longs for the peace she feels there. She tries to refuse to leave, but Attila forces her to accompany the Huns out of the city. The next night, Attila gathers the Barbarian leaders and announces that they will attack Rome immediately. As soon as his soothsayer announces that the signs are positive, a bolt of lightning strikes a tree that falls on him. Although this concerns the Huns, Attila names it a good omen. Soon after, his men bring two captured monks to him, and Attila, who does not dare anger the Christian God, orders the soldiers killed. The monks then beg him not to kill the soldiers, baffling Attila.\n\nAs the Huns gather outside Rome, Marcian, finding no help for Valentinian with Theodosius, prepares to flee the palace, but is captured upon stopping to bid Pulcheria goodbye. While Attila's new seer, whom he calls Persian, relates a vision of Marcian as emperor, Paulinus releases Marcian from the dungeon and the two sneak into Pulcheria's. Together, they decide to gather the army against Theodosius and install Pulcheria to the throne. After Theodosius is forced to abdicate, Pulcheria names Marcian her top general and announces her plans to travel to Rome with him and their army to help guard its walls. Meanwhile, Persian is plagued by visions of God and martyrs in the clouds calling for Attila's death, and Attila remembers an image his childhood nurse saw in which he died under the shadow of a cross. Though fearful, he continues to disregard the signs. When Marcian reaches Rome, he finds Valentinian leaving, but retains two battalions to add to his own to protect the city.\n\nThat night, Attila orders the attack, but stops when [[Pope Leo I]] arrives to name Rome the temple of God and foresee Attila's downfall, as portended by the lightning strike. Afterward, Attila realizes that Kubra must have told the Pope about the lightning, and, though he is heartbroken, kills her for betraying him. In his sleep that night, he sees a vision of the martyrs marching against him and, crazed, orders the Huns to retreat. Marcian hears and immediately plans to ambush Attila when he reaches the nearest city. The surprise attack demolishes the Huns, who soon fall. Marcian finds Attila and duels with him, but it is Ilduco, who has spent the last months overflowing with rage, who drives the fatal dagger into his chest. As prophesied, Attila dies with the sword's handle forming the shadow of a cross on the ground. Days later, Pulcheria reunites the halves of the empire and names Marcian emperor, to the delight of the Roman people.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]] as [[Marcian]]\n* [[Jack Palance]] as [[Attila]]\n* [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] as Princess [[Pulcheria]]\n* [[Rita Gam]] as Kubra\n* [[Jeff Morrow]] as General Paulinus\n* [[George Dolenz]] as Emperor [[Theodosius II]]\n* [[Eduard Franz]] as Astrologer\n* [[Allison Hayes]] as [[Ildico]]\n* [[Alexander Scourby]] as [[Chrysaphius]]\n* [[Howard Petrie]] as [[Gundahar]]\n* [[Michael Ansara]] as Edecon\n* [[Leo Gordon]] as [[Bleda]]\n* [[Moroni Olsen]] as [[Pope Leo I]]\n* Fred Nurney as Chamberlain\n* [[Sara Shane]] as Myra\n* [[Pat Hogan]] as [[Sangiban]]\n* Robo Bechi as Chilothe \n* Charles Horvath as Olt\n* Glenn Thompson as Seyte\n* Chuck Robertson as Mirrai\n* [[Walter Coy]] as Emperor [[Valentinian III]]\n* [[Rusty Westcoatt]] as Tula \n* Norbert Schiller as Seer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was announced by Universal in October 1953.<ref>{{cite news|title=U-I Will Continue Heavy Film Output: Studio Plan 34 Features for New Year in Contrast With Rivals' Cutback Program|first=Thomas M.|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times |date=27 October 1953|page= 32}}</ref> [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] was to make her dramatic debut in the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ballerina Doffs Shoes for Movie: Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina Will Make U. S. Film Debut in Dramatic Role in 'Sign of the Pagan'|author=Thomas M. Pryor|work=New York Times|date=26 November 1953|page=51}}</ref> She was a ballerina who had been signed to a long-term contract to Universal after a series of screen tests, including some with Jeff Chandler. Chandler was assigned the male lead and Douglas Sirk given the job of directing. The movie was going to be Universal's first using Cinemascope.<ref>{{cite news|title=Looking at Hollywood: 'Conquest of Space' to Be Film Without a Star|last=Hopper|first=Hedda|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=28 November 1953|page=15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dowling to Make Film of Hurricane: Tropic Storm to Be Protagonist of Movie Seen Through Eyes of Air Force Weather Men|last=Pryor|first=Thomas M.|work=New York Times|date=28 November 1953|page=11}}</ref> Jack Palance, then coming off a second Oscar nomination, soon signed to play Attila the Hun. Chandler told [[Hedda Hopper]] that the role was the best he had ever had and that the movie would be Universal's most expensive of that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: CinemaScope to Be Used for 'Venetian'|work=Los Angeles Times|date=7 December 1953|page=A14}}</ref>\n\nJeff Morrow had a two-film-a-year deal with Universal and appeared in ''Sign of the Pagan'' as the second film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Studios Explain Filming Abroad: Council Lists 5 Reasons for Rise -- Cites Backgrounds, Better Financing Deals|author=Thomas M. Pryor|work=New York Times|date=11 December 1953|page=42}}</ref> Allison Hayes was a model who was spotted by the wife of [[Earl Warren]] at a party in Washington. Mrs Warren suggested she try her luck in Hollywood and she succeeded in getting a contract with Universal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: 'Track of the Cat' Wellman's Next Film|work=Los Angeles Times|date=12 May 1954|page=B8}}</ref> She played Attila's young wife; Jack Palance injured her during their love scenes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: Fuller Will Direct Next Film in Britain|work=Los Angeles Times|date=29 January 1954|page=A6}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAnother film about Attila the Hun came out around the same time, ''Attila'', starring [[Anthony Quinn]] in the title role.<ref>{{cite news|title=Attila Strikes Twice|author=|work=New York Times|date=7 November 1954|page=SM78}}</ref>\n\nA novelisation of the script by Roger Fuller was published in 1955 in time for the film's release.<ref>{{cite news|title=With Toga and Gladius: Sign of the Pagan. By Roger Fuller. 373 pp. New York. Dial Press|last=Chubb|first=Thomas Caldecot|work=New York Times|date=9 January 1955|page=BR23}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed sequel==\nUniversal bought a script by Harold Lamb, ''Hannibal of Cathage'' as a possible sequel, to also star Jack Palance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drama: 'Hannibal of Carthage' Epical Project; Diana Lynn, Corey Stage Team|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=17 March 1954|page=19}}</ref> However, it was never made.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0047490}}\n*[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/90104/Sign-of-the-Pagan/ ''Sign of the Pagan''] at [[TCMDB]]\n*[https://archive.org/details/variety196-1954-11/page/n68/mode/1up/search/%22jeff+chandler%22?q=%22jeff+chandler%22 Review of film] at ''Variety'\n* {{YouTube|7Sfls2IjqzI|''Sign of the Pagan'' film clip}}\n\n{{Douglas Sirk |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sign Of The Pagan}}\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Douglas Sirk]]\n[[Category:1954 films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 5th century]]\n[[Category:1950s historical films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Attila the Hun]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Hans J. Salter]]\n", "name_user": "PrairieCat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign_of_the_Pagan"}
{"title_page": "Busanjin District First (South Korean Legislature Constituency)", "text_new": "{{AFC submission|t||ts=20200407171911|u=Michaelhill94|ns=118}}\n{{AFC submission|t||ts=20200407133613|u=Michaelhill94|ns=118|demo=}}<!-- Important, do not remove this line before article has been created. -->\n\nBusanjin District First is a constituency in Busan represented in the [[National Assembly of the Republic of Korea]]. It is one of the [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|253 constituencies]] that  elects one assembly member by the [[first past the post]] system of election, and was created before the [[1988 South Korean legislative election]]. It is currently represented by [[Kim Young-chun]] of the [[_Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Kim Young-chun Korean wiki\">{{cite web |url=https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EA%B9%80%EC%98%81%EC%B6%98_(1962%EB%85%84)}}</ref> It was previously a safe seat for the [[United Future Party]] but is now a marginal.   \n\n=Location and History= \n\n[[File:\uad6d\ud68c\uc120\uac70\uad6c \ubd80\uc0b0\uc9c4\uad6c\uac11.svg|thumb|Location of Busanjin District First Constituency within Busan]]\n\nThe constituency represents the northern part of the [[Busanjin District]]<ref name=\"Busan Jin First Korean wiki\">{{cite web |url=https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EB%B6%80%EC%82%B0%EC%A7%84%EA%B5%AC_%EA%B0%91 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n=Elections= \n\n==[[2020 South Korean legislative election]]<ref name=\"Naver candidates list\">{{cite web |url=https://news.naver.com/main/election/nation2020/candidate/index.nhn |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Candidate !! Party !! Votes !! % !! +-%\n|-\n| Kim Young-chun || [[_Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] ||  ||  || \n|-\n| Seo Byeong-soo || [[United Future Party]] || || || \n|-\n| Kim Tae-soo|| [[Party for People's Livelihoods]] || ||  || \n|-\n| Kim Jung-hee || [[National Revolutionary Dividends Party]] ||  ||  || \n|-\n| J